		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>So is there any solution how to stop the brute force attempts?</p>
		</div>

		
		
	</article>
	<ul class="children">

	<li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="comment-2559">
	<article >

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/5ea8cc42e745b2af458913403239c5c9?s=48&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/5ea8cc42e745b2af458913403239c5c9?s=96&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' loading='lazy'/><span itemprop="name">Randy</span> 			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2013-04-12T11:37:00-07:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/2013/04/mass-wordpress-brute-force-attacks-myth-or-reality.html#comment-2559">April 12, 2013</a></time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>There are several ways that you could stop these wordpress plugins. Firewalls or modsecurity as mentioned in the post, you can install wordpress plugins such as stealth login page, limit login attempts, wordfence. You could also use .htaccess to limit access to the wp-login and wp-admin pages to only ip addresses that need to be connecting to it.</p>
		</div>

		
		
	</article>
